why do certain employers prefer telephone interviews to traditional interviews in general a phone interview will be the first step before an in person interview consider this the hiring manager has applications or resumes to look over he scans through them and weeds out the ones who aren't qualified that might narrow it down to then he goes through them again picks out the best he sets appointments for phone screens or he calls them up sees if it's now would work for a phone screen he'll spend anywhere from minutes to an hour on the phone asking questions it could be called a qia are they qualified interested affordable he's trying to determine which candidates he'd like to bring in for a personal interview he might choose a couple of them or even five of them to bring in if a candidate needs to interview with several folks it's hard to line up everyone's schedules and find a time when everyone is in the office i hope this helps you figure it out Brian Lenihan Bluetooth Enterprise content management Expert system The Apprentice 2 Social rule Constitution of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Telephone tapping Television Photography Plame affair Killian documents Patrick Hillery Online Copyright Infringement Liability Limitation Act Telephone exchange Password Al Gore presidential campaign, 2000 Customer relationship management Mobile phone Graduate school 24 (television) Steve Jobs Job interview The Empty Child Call centre Contredanse George Brown, Baron George-Brown Windows 2000 Constitution of Fiji: Chapter 6 Software engineering Donald Neilson Winning Streak GSM services Requirements analysis Canadian House of Commons Tag Emergency telephone number Probation officer Private branch exchange Wal-Mart Education in Germany Desmond O'Malley Education in the People's Republic of China Avalanche Political campaign Instant-runoff voting United Kingdom corporation tax Holy Orders Microeconomics Digital photography Air traffic controller Time Out of Mind Taxicab Maryl